Data for this exercise are taken from the paper “X-ray luminosities of SDSS DR7 clusters from RASS” (Wang+, 2014). The file clusters_xrays.csv contains data for a number of galaxy clusters. Specifically, the columns in the files are:

• LX: absolute luminosity in the X-ray

• Ngal: number of galaxies in the cluster

You want to use these data to estimate the Ngal-Log10(luminosity) relation to be used in future observations to estimate the Number of galaxies from the logarithm of the X-ray luminosity.

Using an MCMC software of your choice, write a Bayesian linear regression model to estimate the unknown regression coeﬀicients.

Plot the estimated posterior distributions of the parameters of the linear model, and summarize your results with your best estimate for the parameters and their 95% credibility intervals.

Plot the data and overplot your best-fit line with the 95% credibility region on the data.

Clusters of galaxies can only be identified if they contain at least 3 galaxies. How do you this this impacts your regression result? Use a MC simulation to justify your conclusion. BONUS: If you have time, using the file GC_allcolumns.txt on canvas, extend the globular cluster analysis we saw in class to simultaneously include: the absolute luminosity M_V [col10] and the “Dynamical mass” of the galaxy [col21]. You may want to consider the Log of the Masses. 1

#Normal Model

model = pm.Model()
N = len(galaxies)

with model as poisson_log:

    x = pm.MutableData('x',luminosity)
    y = pm.MutableData('y',galaxies)

    # Priors for unknown model parameters
    alpha = pm.Normal('alpha', mu=3, sigma=0.5, initval=1) #Offset so doesn't shoot to infinity
    beta = pm.Normal('beta', mu=0, sigma=0.2, initval=1)

    # Linear model and exponential link
    mu = alpha + beta*x
    mu_y = pm.Deterministic('mu_y',pm.math.exp(mu))
    dispersion = pm.Deterministic('dispersion',pm.math.sum(((y - np.exp(mu))/np.sqrt(np.exp(mu)))**2/(N-2)))

    # Likelihood (sampling distribution) of observations
    Y_obs = pm.Poisson('yobs', mu=pm.math.exp(mu), observed=y)
    trace = pm.sample(draws=10000)
